          "body": "Ezra 7 opens with a genealogy that is simultaneously a credential and a theological claim. Sixteen generations are traced, moving backward from Ezra to Aaron the chief priest (v. 5) — a lineage that skips several names known from Chronicles (indicating selection, not exhaustion) but carefully preserves the names of Phinehas (whose zeal for holiness is celebrated in Numbers 25:10-13), Zadok (David's faithful priest, 2 Samuel 8:17), and Hilkiah (the priest who found the Book of the Law in Josiah's day, 2 Kings 22:8). These are not random ancestors; they are the men whose names mark high points of priestly faithfulness in Israel's history. Ezra is introduced as heir to the best of Israel's priestly tradition.\n\nVerse 6 then adds a title that has no strict genealogical function: 'a scribe skilled in the law of Moses.' The double identity — Aaronic priest AND Torah scribe — is unusual and programmatic. The priest without the Word is a ritualist; the scribe without priestly accountability is a theorist. Ezra is both. He is the answer to the specific post-exilic deficit: a community with a functioning temple (built in Ezra 1-6) but without functioning Torah instruction. Derek Kidner observes that the genealogy is 'not a vanity but a validity check' — in a community anxious about the legitimacy of its leadership, Ezra's unbroken chain to Aaron establishes him as the genuine article.\n\nThe final clause of v. 6 — 'the king granted him all he requested because the hand of the LORD his God was upon him' — is the narrator's first interpretive declaration. The extraordinary favor of a Persian king toward a Jewish scribe is not explained by Ezra's brilliance, networking, or political skill. It is explained by the divine hand. The chapter will use this formula three more times (vv. 9, 28 twice), building a cumulative case that every door Ezra walks through has been opened from the inside by God."
