          "body": "Verse 10 is the chapter's biographical center and arguably the most important verse in the book of Ezra. It is positioned between the account of the journey (vv. 7-9) and the text of the royal decree (vv. 11-26), as if the narrator wants to ensure the reader does not miss its significance. Before any decree is read, before any resources are allocated, before any judicial authority is granted, the chapter insists on this: 'Ezra had set his heart.'\n\nThe verb *kun* (set, established, prepared) carries the sense of deliberate, sustained orientation — the same word used of David's preparation of materials for the temple (1 Chronicles 22:14) and of the steadied heart of the trusting man in Psalm 57:7. Ezra's heart was *established* toward Torah, not merely interested in it. This is a volitional act, not a spiritual mood. And the object of that established heart is a three-stage sequence that functions as the paradigm for every Torah minister: *study* (*darash* — to seek out, investigate diligently), *practice* (*asah* — to do, to perform), *teach* (*lamad* — to instruct others). The sequence is non-negotiable and non-reversible. Teaching without practice is hypocrisy; practice without study is presumption; study without the aim of teaching privatizes what is given for the community.\n\nThis verse explains why the hand of God was on Ezra (v. 9). Ezra's preparation preceded the commission; God's favor rested on a man whose private orientation had already been shaped by the Word. Howard Hendricks put it plainly: 'You cannot impart what you do not possess.' The hand of God in vv. 6, 9, 28 is not the explanation for Ezra's success despite his preparation — it is the divine ratification of it. Charles Spurgeon makes the same connection in his own words: 'God does not put His best gifts in unprepared hands.' The verse is not a works-righteousness statement; it is a stewardship-of-calling statement."
