          "title": "The decree as instrument of providence (7:11-26)",
          "body": "The royal decree of Artaxerxes occupies the longest single block of the chapter (vv. 11-26) and is preserved in Aramaic — the official imperial language, signaling authentic documentary source material. The narrator's preservation of the decree verbatim is itself a theological statement: this is real history, real power, real money, real judicial authority, all being bent toward the purposes of the God of heaven.\n\nThe decree has four movements. First (vv. 13-16), voluntary permission: any Israelite, priest, or Levite in the kingdom may go with Ezra. The going is *nedav* (willing, spontaneous) — God's covenant purposes are advanced through unconstrained human decision, not imperial conscription. Second (vv. 17-20), financial provision: Ezra carries the king's own freewill offerings of silver and gold, plus whatever additional freewill gifts the diaspora provides, all designated for temple sacrifice and temple needs. The Persian treasury becomes a conduit for Levitical offerings. Third (vv. 21-24), imperial enforcement: treasurers throughout Trans-Euphrates are commanded to supply whatever Ezra requires, and all temple personnel are permanently exempted from taxation. Fourth (vv. 25-26), judicial commission: Ezra is empowered to appoint judges, instruct the ignorant, and enforce compliance — with sanctions extending to death, banishment, confiscation of goods, or imprisonment.\n\nThe scale of the commission is staggering. Artaxerxes is not merely allowing a Jewish scribe to travel home; he is effectively establishing Torah as the governing law for the entire satrapy of Trans-Euphrates and granting one man the authority to enforce it. The recurring title 'the God of heaven' (vv. 12, 21, 23) is the Persian court's acknowledgment that Israel's God has universal jurisdiction — what the decree does politically is what Ezra 7:27 will confirm theologically: the king's heart was moved, and the provision issued from the God who moved it."
