          "body": "The chapter's final two verses mark a seismic shift. Artaxerxes' name has dominated the Aramaic section; now Ezra speaks in his own voice, in Hebrew, in the first person, and his first word is *barakh* — blessed. The shift from third-person narrative to first-person doxology is not merely a stylistic change; it is a hermeneutical one. Ezra is showing the reader how to read everything that came before. The correct interpretation of a Persian king's extraordinary decree is not 'Artaxerxes was favorably disposed' but 'the LORD, the God of our fathers, put such a thing as this in the king's heart.'\n\nThe doxology has two movements. Verse 27 blesses God for two acts: putting the intention in the king's heart, and adorning the house of the LORD in Jerusalem. Both are God's acts accomplished through Artaxerxes' agency — the king is the instrument, not the initiator. Verse 28 then applies the same logic personally: God has 'extended lovingkindness (*chesed*) to me before the king and his counselors and before all the king's mighty princes.' The word *chesed* is the chapter's most theologically loaded term — it is covenant faithfulness, the loyal love by which God keeps His promises to His people (Exodus 34:6-7; Psalm 136). Ezra does not experience imperial favor as political luck; he receives it as the covenant God's specific act of faithfulness toward him.\n\nThe result, verse 28 concludes, is that Ezra 'was strengthened' (*chazaq* — the same verb used of Joshua at the threshold of Canaan, Joshua 1:6-9) and gathered leading men to go up with him. Providence produces courage. The man who traces every open door to God's hand is not passively fatalistic — he is actively energized to lead. This pattern — traced providence producing strengthened resolve — is the chapter's closing pastoral gift to the reader."
