          "body": "A reading of Ezra 7 that ignores the sixty-year gap between chapters 6 and 7 misses the chapter's canonical weight. The temple had been standing since 516 BC. By 458 BC, two generations of returnees had lived with a rebuilt sanctuary but — as chapters 9-10 will reveal — with rampant intermarriage with surrounding peoples, compromised covenant identity, and no functioning judicial infrastructure grounded in Torah. The building was complete; the community was not.\n\nThis is the book of Ezra's structural theology: physical restoration (the house, chapters 1-6) is necessary but insufficient without spiritual and legal restoration (the Word and its enforcement, chapters 7-10). The temple without Torah produces a form of godliness without its power. It took a second man — not Zerubbabel the builder but Ezra the scribe — to complete what the first return began. The sequence is not coincidental; it reflects a consistent biblical pattern in which the Word of God must inhabit and govern what God builds. Solomon's temple required the giving of the law at Sinai before it was theologically intelligible. The second temple required Ezra's Torah mission before it was communally functional.\n\nFor the reader of the whole canon, the pattern extends forward: the church built by Pentecost (Acts 2) requires the apostolic teaching (Acts 2:42) without which it is merely an institution. The hand of God resting on the mission of Word-ministry (v. 9) is not an Old Testament curiosity — it is the operating logic of every era in which God intends to form a people who know His law, live His law, and pass it on."
