    "intro": "Interpretation moves from observation (what the text says) to discerning the author's theological intent in its original setting. Ezra 7 operates on three levels simultaneously: the biographical (who Ezra is and why he is qualified), the political (how Persian imperial power serves divine covenant purposes), and the doxological (how a man of God correctly interprets his own circumstances). The four movements below follow the chapter's argument through these levels, with attention to canonical cross-references and the theological weight of key Hebrew and Aramaic terms.",
