        "excerpt": "This Ezra went up from Babylon, and he was a scribe skilled in the law of Moses, which the LORD God of Israel had given; and the king granted him all he requested because the hand of the LORD his God was upon him.",
        "body": "The genealogy of verses 1-5 performs a theological function that modern readers are tempted to skip. In the post-exilic community, priestly legitimacy was existential — the gatekeeping lists of Ezra 2:61-63 had already excluded priests who could not document their ancestry. Ezra's sixteen-generation chain to Aaron is therefore not genealogical decoration; it is credential-establishment for a man who will shortly claim authority to adjudicate the entire community's covenantal standing. The selective nature of the list (it omits names found in the fuller Chronicles lists) shows that the narrator chooses names for their theological resonance: Phinehas (Numbers 25), whose zeal for holiness was credited as righteousness; Zadok (2 Samuel 8:17), the priest who remained faithful through Absalom's rebellion; Hilkiah (2 Kings 22:8), who found the lost Book of the Law under Josiah. The genealogy is not biography — it is a theology of faithfulness-under-pressure, with Ezra placed as the heir of those who held the line when others compromised.\n\nVerse 6 adds to the priestly identity a scribal one: *saphar mahir* (a scribe skilled, literally 'quick' or 'ready,' carrying the sense of professional mastery). The same word *mahir* is used in Psalm 45:1 of the tongue of a skilled (*mahir*) writer. Ezra does not merely know the Torah — he is fluent in it, expert in its exposition, capable of handling it with precision. This is the competence side of his calling; verse 10 will name the character side. Neither is sufficient without the other.\n\nThe double explanation in verse 6 — the king granted all he requested — sets the pattern for the chapter's entire theological method. Two realities are simultaneously true: Artaxerxes grants generously, AND the hand of the LORD is the reason. The narrator refuses to choose between human agency and divine sovereignty. Both are real; neither cancels the other. This is the Ezra-Nehemiah theology of providence: God accomplishes His purposes through real human decisions, real imperial politics, real journeys with real dangers, and real risks — while remaining the controlling agent behind every open door.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Saphar mahir* (skilled scribe) — *mahir* from *mahar*, to be quick, fleet, expert. *Yad YHWH* (hand of the LORD) — the anthropomorphic expression for God's active power in history; it appears in the exodus narrative (Exodus 9:3; Deuteronomy 2:15), the wilderness (Numbers 11:23), and the conquest (Joshua 4:24). Ezra's use of it (vv. 6, 9, 28) is a deliberate exodus-echo."
