        "body": "Verse 10 is the chapter's pivot, positioned at the exact center of its structure — after the journey summary and before the decree. Its placement is a narrative signal: before the reader hears what Artaxerxes authorized Ezra to do, the narrator insists on why Ezra could be trusted with that authorization. The three infinitives — *darash* (study), *asah* (practice), *lamad* (teach) — are not a job description; they are a spiritual biography compressed into one sentence.\n\n*Darash* carries more weight than casual reading. It is the verb of diligent inquiry, of seeking out with intensity — the same root that lies behind the later Hebrew *midrash* (exposition). Ezra does not skim the Torah; he investigates it. *Asah* (to do, to practice) is the bridge between knowledge and character — the word used throughout the Torah for covenant obedience ('you shall *do* these statutes,' Leviticus 18:5). The sequence *darash* → *asah* prevents the knowledge of Torah from becoming academic credential detached from moral formation. *Lamad* (to teach) is the outward expression of the inward formation — the transfer to the community of what has been received and lived. Deuteronomy 4:5 places the same sequence in Moses' mouth: 'I have taught (*lamad*) you statutes and rules, as the LORD my God commanded me.' Ezra is explicitly a new Moses figure in the narrative of post-exilic restoration.\n\nThe phrase 'set his heart' (*kun levav*) deserves attention. The Hebrew *kun* is used for things that are established, fixed, secured — a foundation, a throne, a determined purpose. Ezra's orientation toward Torah is not a seasonal enthusiasm; it is a settled disposition of the will. This is what makes him qualified not merely for the teaching role but for the judicial one (v. 25). A man whose heart is established toward the Word will apply it without favoritism; a man whose relationship to the Word is contingent will bend the Word toward convenience.\n\nH.G.M. Williamson (Word Biblical Commentary) rightly observes that verse 10 is 'the key to understanding the whole chapter' — it explains both the divine favor of vv. 6-9 and the royal commission of vv. 11-26. Derek Kidner (Tyndale OT) adds that the sequence 'is the order that cannot be reversed: to teach what one does not practice is hypocrisy; to practice what one has not studied is presumption.' The verse is the most portable pastoral principle in the book.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kun lev* (set the heart) — the verb *kun* in Polel stem (intensive): to establish, make firm, prepare thoroughly. Compare 1 Chronicles 22:14 (David *kun* the temple materials) and Psalm 57:7 (*kun* my heart). *Darash* (study) — to seek out, investigate; root of *midrash*. *Lamad* (teach) — the Piel (intensive) form means to teach diligently, to train."
